pull_request.title: Add hardcover author statistic and rename novel chart
pull_request.body:
This pull request adds a new statistics feature that displays a bar chart of Maddrax-Hardcover counts per author, both in the backend and frontend. It introduces reward gating for this chart, updates configuration and tests, and ensures the feature is only visible to users with sufficient points. The changes are grouped into backend logic, frontend integration, configuration, and testing.

**Backend logic and data aggregation:**
* Added calculation of `hardcoverAuthorCounts` in `StatistikController.php` to count Maddrax-Hardcover books per author, including co-authors.
* Passed the new `hardcoverAuthorCounts` data to the view for rendering.

**Frontend integration:**
* Added a new card in `index.blade.php` that displays the "Maddrax-Hardcover je Autor:in" bar chart, visible only to users with ≥41 points. Chart data is injected via JavaScript.
* Updated `statistik.js` to render the new hardcover author chart using the provided data.

**Configuration updates:**
* Added a new reward entry for the hardcover author chart in `config/rewards.php`, including title, description, and points threshold.
* Clarified the title and description for the existing novels-per-author chart.

**Testing:**
* Added feature tests to verify the visibility of the hardcover author chart based on user points in `StatistikTest.php`.
* Added a test for the reward visibility in `RewardControllerTest.php`.
* Updated Jest tests to confirm the chart is rendered on DOMContentLoaded.

**Test data preparation:**
* Updated test data creation to include author information for hardcovers, ensuring accurate chart generation in tests.

Publish incredibly high performance websites and applications right from GitHub. The Netlify platform connects your repositories to an all-in-one workflow for global CDN deployment, continuous integration, and automatic (and free) HTTPS. Each time you commit changes, Netlify builds your site, prerenders markup, and optimizes assets on dedicated build infrastructure. Easily create an entirely automated workflows for your web applications

## Features

### Push your site live, directly from GitHub
Deploy your site to an ultra-redundant global CDN that’s purpose built for serving pages and assets quickly and consistently.

### Automate deployment
Netlify’s built-in Continuous Deployment automatically runs your build commands and deploys the result whenever you push to your Git repository.

### Add a custom domain
Purchase domains and manage DNS zones and records right inside of Netlify.

### HTTPS is automatic
Your site will automatically be secured with a free TLS certificate from Let’s Encrypt.

### Deploy Previews
Netlify’s Deploy Previews streamlined your workflow by giving you a unique, permanent URL to check what your changes will be like in production whenever you submit a pull request.

### And a lot more!
Netlify includes solutions for forms, identity, and even custom functions powered by AWS Lambda. And all this functionality can be configured directly in your repo.

Amazon Q Developer is a generative AI assistant that enables you to automate code changes and legacy code transformation, all from a GitHub issue. After completing its code changes, Amazon Q Developer generates a pull request for your review. Start with 500 invocations per month of Amazon Q Developer’s feature development and code review capabilities and 10,000 lines of Java transformations per month. Increase your usage at any time by registering your Amazon Q Developer app installation with your AWS account.

# Feature development

Amazon Q Developer allows you to generate code directly from natural language prompts. You can build new features, debug, refine algorithms by describing your requests and letting Amazon Q Developer perform the tasks. It can help to save time, reduce errors, and improve efficiency with code generation that evolves with your project.

# Code transformation

Amazon Q Developer transforms outdated codebases into scalable, efficient, and maintainable systems. You can update your technology stack, enhance performance, and ensure future compatibility while preserving the core functionality of your existing code. With Amazon Q Developer, you can avoid technical debt and build your applications for long-term implications.

# Code review

With Amazon Q Developer, you can automate code reviews within GitHub. When Amazon Q Developer performs a code review, it analyzes your pull requests, provides feedback on code quality, potential issues, and security concerns. Amazon Q Developer then provides suggestions based on the code review.


# Getting started

1. Select the GitHub repositories that can use Amazon Q Developer and complete the authorization process.
2. Get started using Amazon Q Developer in an issue by adding labels for feature development or code transformation, or by creating a new pull request for code review.

Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress. Original issue description: > [Ref Issue #10241](https://github.com/elastic/security-team/issues/10241)

**Motivation** > When users opt for a manual deployment today, they have the option to deploy an agent on macOS, Windows, RPM, and DEB. However, Cloudbeat only supports Linux and Kubernetes. > While it’s true that the same agent policy may include other integrations supporting these operating systems, it doesn’t make sense to propose these options after our integration installation. > > The goal of this ticket is to update the warning text to be much more explicit about our inability to work on those options. > > > > > > > **Definition of done** > - [ ] Update the warning text to be much more explicit about our inability to work on those options. pull_request.title: bug: Fix undefined Inno `AppVersion`
pull_request.body: ## Pull Request Description It seems to be that there is an issue where the `FLADDER_VERSION` environment variable is not defined so the inno installer defaults to latest everytime. This causes several issues such as: - Inno installer just saying latest - App Version in Settings/Control Panel saying latest - Issues with creating new Winget manifests This PR should fix this issue by overwriting the inno installer file with the latest version. ## Issue Being Fixed Inno installer version not being defined correctly. ## Screenshots / Recordings Before: After: ## Checklist - [ ] If a new package was added, did you ensure it works for all supported platforms? Is the package well maintained - [ ] Check that any changes are related to the issue at hand.

pull_request.title: Fix CI workflow structure validation and enhance build failure prevention
pull_request.body:
This PR addresses the CI build failures reported in the Mergify CI Insights by fixing workflow structure validation and implementing comprehensive CI failure prevention measures.

## Problem

The Mergify CI Insights Report showed build failures in the "Build LaTeX PDF" workflow, indicating potential CI pipeline instability. Investigation revealed that the workflow structure validation test (`test_issue_743_validation.py`) had an outdated expected structure that didn't account for the "Enhanced pre-build validation" step added in issue #761, potentially missing edge cases that could cause CI failures.

## Solution

### 1. Fixed Workflow Structure Validation

Updated `test_issue_743_validation.py` to properly validate the complete 8-step workflow structure:

```python
# Before: Missing enhanced validation step
expected_steps = [
    'Checkout repository',
    'Set up Python', 
    'Install Python dependencies',
    'Run LaTeX syntax validation',
    'Run CTMM Build System Check',
    'Run comprehensive CI validation',
    'Set up LaTeX'  # Step 7
]

# After: Complete workflow structure
expected_steps = [
    'Checkout repository',
    'Set up Python',
    'Install Python dependencies', 
    'Run LaTeX syntax validation',
    'Run CTMM Build System Check',
    'Run comprehensive CI validation',
    'Enhanced pre-build validation',  # Step 7
    'Set up LaTeX'                    # Step 8
]
```

### 2. Created Comprehensive CI Failure Prevention Test

Added `test_issue_811_fix.py` that validates CI robustness across multiple dimensions:
- **Workflow Structure Integrity**: Validates all 11 workflow steps are properly ordered
- **Critical Validation Steps**: Ensures all 4 validation steps are present and execute before LaTeX compilation
- **LaTeX Action Stability**: Confirms stable `dante-ev/latex-action@v2` version (prevents issue #735 recurrence)
- **Error Handling**: Validates proper artifact collection and failure recovery
- **Validation Chain**: Tests that all validation scripts execute successfully in sequence

### 3. Comprehensive Documentation

Created `ISSUE_811_RESOLUTION.md` with detailed technical analysis, prevention guidelines, and future maintenance instructions.

## Results

All validation tests now pass successfully:
- ✅ Issue #811 specific validation: 3/3 tests passed
- ✅ Workflow structure validation: 5/5 tests passed (now correctly validates steps 7-8)
- ✅ CI robustness validation: 5/5 tests passed
- ✅ Complete validation chain executes successfully

The CI pipeline now provides systematic protection against build failures with:
- Multi-layer validation before expensive LaTeX compilation
- Stable dependency versions
- Comprehensive error handling and logging
- Robust testing coverage for all failure prevention measures

Fixes #811.
